[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   observed pacing delays may be higher than the threshold when paced thread spent more
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   time in the pacing code. It usually happens when thread is de-scheduled while paced,
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   OS takes longer to unblock the thread, or JVM experiences an STW pause.
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ] 
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   Higher delay would prevent application outpacing the GC, but it will hide the GC latencies
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   from the STW pause times. Pacing affects the individual threads, and so it would also be
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   invisible to the usual profiling tools, but would add up to end-to-end application latency.
[2026-04-03T02:25:33.154+0600][95.658s][info][gc,stats    ]   Raise max pacing delay with care.
